      <p>Taken together, these observations mean the third generation sequencing technologies can theoretically provide complete genome sequences for most prokaryotic organisms if the error rate is controlled or corrected by other short read sequencing technologies. On the other hand, bigger eukaryotic genomes, which are likely to have more complex repeat structure, would benefit less from the longer reads produced by third generation sequencing technologies.</p>
